<subSubSection id="D88E06D1FFE2FF94AFF9FB14FE62C131" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph id="902B555AFFE2FF94AFF9FB14FD42C3FB" blockId="98.[192,743,1249,1276]" box="[192,743,1249,1276]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AFF9FB14FEFCC3FC" bold="true" box="[192,345,1249,1276]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">
<typeStatus id="4F2FEBF8FFE2FF94AFF9FB14FF5CC3FB" box="[192,249,1250,1276]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Type</typeStatus>
species.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="57942ED9FFE2FF94AE66FB14FD46C3FB" authority="Hewitson, 1878" authorityName="Hewitson" authorityYear="1878" box="[351,739,1249,1276]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Astictopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ozias">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AE66FB14FD8EC3FC" box="[351,555,1250,1276]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Astictopterus ozias</emphasis>
Hewitson, 1878
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="902B555AFFE2FF94AFF9FAFDFE62C131" blockId="98.[191,1442,1291,1590]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AFF9FAFDFEE4C222" bold="true" box="[192,321,1291,1317]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Definition.</emphasis>
Superficially very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="57942ED9FFE2FF94ADB2FAFDFB67C222" authority="(Godman and Salvin, 1879)" baseAuthorityName="Godman and Salvin" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[651,1218,1291,1317]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lychnuchoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saptine">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94ADB2FAFDFCDBC222" box="[651,894,1291,1317]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Lychnuchoides saptine</emphasis>
(Godman and Salvin, 1879)
</taxonomicName>
, the 
<typeStatus id="4F2FEBF8FFE2FF94ABC3FAFAFA8FC221" box="[1274,1322,1292,1318]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName id="57942ED9FFE2FF94AFFBFADBFDB4C240" authority="Godman, 1901" authorityName="Godman" authorityYear="1901" box="[194,529,1325,1351]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lychnuchoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AFFBFADBFEC5C240" box="[194,352,1325,1351]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Lychnuchoides</emphasis>
Godman, 1901
</taxonomicName>
and was placed in it. However, not monophyletic with 
<taxonomicName id="57942ED9FFE2FF94ABACFAD8FAA7C240" baseAuthorityName="Godman and Salvin" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[1173,1282,1326,1351]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lychnuchoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saptine">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94ABACFAD8FAA7C240" box="[1173,1282,1326,1351]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">L. saptine</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="08AF49DFFFE2FF94AA2AFADBFAC1C240" box="[1299,1380,1325,1351]" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="96.[192,268,1515,1541]" captionTargetBox="[198,1435,215,1477]" captionTargetId="figure-160@96.[192,1440,213,1481]" captionTargetPageId="96" captionText="Figure 17. Genomic tree of Carystina, Pericharini, Megathymini and relatives. Clades corresponding to new subtribes described in this work are highlighted in green. See Fig. 1 legend for other notations." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392096" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392096/files/figure.png" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) and instead forms a clade of its own closer to the base of the tree. Keys to K. 
<quantity id="576CF8BFFFE2FF94ACECFAB9FB86C26E" box="[981,1059,1359,1385]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.4422" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" unit="in" value="29.3">29.3 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation id="F40528ABFFE2FF94AB11FAA6FB19C26D" author="Evans WH" box="[1064,1212,1359,1386]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" pagination="54 - 88" refId="ref85135" refString="Evans WH. 1955. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum (Natural History). Part IV. Hesperiinae and Megathyminae. British Museum (Natural History); London. v + 499 p., pl. 54 - 88." type="book chapter" year="1955">Evans (1955)</bibRefCitation>
. Distinguished from its relatives by the following combination of characters: apiculus of antennae obtuse (not angled); nudum of about 13 segments; mid-tibiae without spines; males with a narrow stigma on forewing, no brands; gnathos developed, not as broad as in many relatives, arms converging, separated from uncus in lateral view; harpe expanded in the middle, longer than valva. See comments below about wing pattern characters. In DNA, a combination of the following base pairs is diagnostic: aly291.6.1:G208T, aly971.19.1:T1347C, aly207.8.6:A119G, aly207.8.6:A118C, and aly423.15.3:A165T.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D88E06D1FFE2FF94AFF9F9B3FD62C1B4" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="902B555AFFE2FF94AFF9F9B3FA05C158" blockId="98.[192,1440,1605,1631]" box="[192,1440,1605,1631]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AFF9F9B3FEE1C158" bold="true" box="[192,324,1605,1631]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is a masculine noun in the nominative singular, the first syllable of the 
<typeStatus id="4F2FEBF8FFE2FF94ABE9F9B3FAA5C158" box="[1232,1280,1605,1631]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">type</typeStatus>
species name.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="902B555AFFE2FF94AFF9F998FB48C18E" blockId="98.[192,1261,1646,1673]" box="[192,1261,1646,1673]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AFF9F998FE2CC18F" bold="true" box="[192,393,1646,1672]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Species included.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus id="4F2FEBF8FFE2FF94AEF9F999FE55C18E" box="[448,496,1647,1673]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">type</typeStatus>
species and 
<taxonomicName id="57942ED9FFE2FF94AD45F998FB4CC18E" authority="Salazar and Constantino, 2013" authorityName="Salazar and Constantino" authorityYear="2013" box="[636,1257,1646,1673]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lychnuchoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sebastiani">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AD45F998FC29C18F" box="[636,908,1646,1672]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Lychnuchoides sebastiani</emphasis>
Salazar and Constantino, 2013
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="902B555AFFE2FF94AFF9F96FFD62C1B4" blockId="98.[192,711,1688,1715]" box="[192,711,1688,1715]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AFF9F96FFEF8C1B4" bold="true" box="[192,349,1689,1715]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Parent taxon.</emphasis>
Tribe 
<taxonomicName id="57942ED9FFE2FF94AE9CF96EFD84C1B5" authorityName="Grishin" authorityYear="2019" box="[421,545,1688,1714]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" rank="tribe" tribe="Pericharini">Pericharini</taxonomicName>
Grishin, 2019.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D88E06D1FFE2FF95AFF9F934FBFAC615" lastPageId="99" lastPageNumber="98" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="902B555AFFE2FF95AFF9F934FBFAC615" blockId="98.[192,1441,1730,1927]" lastBlockId="99.[192,1440,214,275]" lastPageId="99" lastPageNumber="98" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AFF9F934FEEDC1DB" bold="true" box="[192,328,1730,1756]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Comments.</emphasis>
The lack of monophyly between 
<taxonomicName id="57942ED9FFE2FF94ADFBF935FCBEC1DB" authorityName="Hewitson" authorityYear="1878" box="[706,795,1731,1757]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Astictopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ozias">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94ADFBF935FCBEC1DB" box="[706,795,1731,1757]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">O. ozias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="57942ED9FFE2FF94AC6CF935FC65C1DB" baseAuthorityName="Godman and Salvin" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[853,960,1731,1756]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lychnuchoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saptine">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AC6CF935FC65C1DB" box="[853,960,1731,1756]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">L. saptine</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
took us by surprise due to close similarity in their wing patterns, for example, a nearly perfect agreement in the outline of forewing yellow patch and the resemblance in pale stripes separating darker patches on ventral hindwing. In the field, the best character to distinguish between the two genera is the pattern on the forewing apex below. In 
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AB1DF8DFFBE1C044" box="[1060,1092,1833,1859]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Oz</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AB69F8DEFB6CC045" bold="true" box="[1104,1225,1832,1858]" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">new genus</emphasis>
, the wing is mostly brown past the yellow discal band, and the pale overscaling starts near the apex, at more than half the distance from the yellow band and apex. In 
<taxonomicName id="57942ED9FFE2FF94AD77F89AFD4EC081" authorityName="Godman" authorityYear="1901" box="[590,747,1900,1926]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lychnuchoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A2E08948FFE2FF94AD77F89AFD4EC081" box="[590,747,1900,1926]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="97">Lychnuchoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the wing is with a smaller brown patch (less than half of the distance from the yellow band to apex along costa) past the yellow discal band, and the rest of the apical area is occupied by pale overscaling, typically with several elongated brown spots inside it.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
